    "outcome": "success",
    "answer": "## Summary of the bug\n\nWhen a user clicks **\"Run\"** (which restarts a task rather than resuming), `RunOneAsync(task, resume: false)` is called, which invokes `ResetStages(task.Id)`. This method:\n\n1. \u2705 First clears all stages to `\"Waiting\"` \n2. \u274c Then reads the **old** `status.json` from the previous run and overwrites stage statuses from it\n\nThis means stages that completed in the previous run get their status set back to `\"Done\"` (green) from the stale disk record. Meanwhile, as the new run fires `stage_start` events, the current stage gets set to `\"Running\"` (also green). The result: **multiple stages appear green/active simultaneously**.\n\nOn a **resume**, reading old status is correct \u2014 the user wants to see where they left off. On a **restart**, the old status is irrelevant since the run starts fresh from stage 1.\n\n## Relevant code\n\n**`MainWindowViewModel.RunOne.cs` line 14** \u2014 always reads old status unconditionally:\n```csharp\nResetStages(task.Id);  // reads stale status.json from disk\n```\n\n**`MainWindowViewModel.Stages.cs` lines 11\u201334** \u2014 `ResetStages` first clears, then re-populates from disk:\n```csharp\nprivate void ResetStages(string? taskId = null)\n{\n    foreach (var stage in Stages) { /* clear all to Waiting */ }\n    if (taskId is null) return;\n    var status = StageStatusRecord.Read(taskDir); // \u2190 loads OLD run's data\n    foreach (var entry in status) { stage.Status = entry.Status; } // overwrites\n}\n```\n\n## Solution options\n\n**Option A** \u2014 Conditional call in `RunOneAsync` (simplest, minimal change)\n\nIn `RunOneAsync`, only read disk status when resuming; for a restart, just clear:\n```csharp\n// Replace: ResetStages(task.Id);\nif (resume)\n    ResetStages(task.Id);\nelse\n    ResetStages();\n```\nThis keeps the API unchanged and matches the semantic difference between restart and resume.\n\n**Option B** \u2014 Add a `clearOnly` parameter to `ResetStages`\n\nMore explicit but adds a parameter that's only meaningful for one call site:\n```csharp\nprivate void ResetStages(string? taskId = null, bool clearOnly = false)\n{\n    // clear all\u2026\n    if (taskId is null || clearOnly) return;\n    // \u2026read from disk\n}\n// In RunOneAsync: ResetStages(task.Id, clearOnly: !resume);\n```\n\n**Option C** \u2014 Delete old `status.json` before calling `ResetStages` on restart\n\nSide-effect-y approach that writes to disk unnecessarily \u2014 worse than Option A/B.\n\n---\n\n```json\n{\n  \"summary\": \"When restarting a task (resume=false), `ResetStages(task.Id)` reads the stale `status.json` from the previous run, resurrecting old \\\"Done\\\" stage statuses. These appear green alongside the new run's current \\\"Running\\\" stage, causing the visual bug of multiple active (green) stages. The fix: only read disk status when resuming; for a restart, just clear all stages to \\\"Waiting\\\".\",\n  \"options\": [\n    \"Option A \u2014 Conditional call in RunOneAsync: replace `ResetStages(task.Id)` with `if (resume) ResetStages(task.Id); else ResetStages();` (simplest, minimal change, keeps API stable)\",\n    \"Option B \u2014 Add `clearOnly` parameter to ResetStages, then call `ResetStages(task.Id, clearOnly: !resume)` from RunOneAsync (more explicit but adds unused parameter for other call sites)\",\n    \"Option C \u2014 Delete the old status.json on disk before calling ResetStages(task.Id) on restart (side-effect-y, writes to disk when not needed)\"\n  ]\n}\n```",
    "exit_code": 0
  },
